## Key Findings

1. **PPO Pilot wins clearly** — the equities-only pilot (+13.81% ARR, Sharpe 0.73) outperforms all baselines and every full cross-asset model. Its lower turnover (0.40 vs ~0.85) suggests it has learned more stable allocations.

2. **Cross-asset expansion hurt performance** — all five full-model variants (including checkpoints) produced negative ARR in 2022–2023. The crash in crypto (BTC, ETH) during 2022 heavily penalised high-turnover strategies.

3. **Equal Weight ≈ MVO** — both baselines produced identical metrics, confirming that MVO with 252-day lookback collapses to near-equal weights on this asset universe during a volatile/down year.

4. **High turnover is costly** — full-model avg turnover (~0.8) incurs significant transaction cost drag. The pilot's 0.40 turnover reflects a smaller, more tractable universe (30 equities vs 32 assets).

## Recommendations

| Priority | Action |
|---|---|
| High | Increase training compute (300k–1M steps) for the full cross-asset regime |
| High | Tune λ (transaction cost) — sensitivity analysis should target λ ∈ [0.001, 0.01] |
| Medium | Evaluate PPO Pilot on out-of-sample 2024 data to test stability |
| Low | Replace fixed-window MVO lookback with an expanding window |

